              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">Bhutan refugees in limbo</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 18px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>Summary: The deportees from Bhutan struggle as the US wants to return them, but their homeland is not welcoming its former citizens.</strong>
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          <strong>The what:</strong> More than two dozen Lhotshampa (ethnic Nepalis expelled from Bhutan in the 1990s) were <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-22-jul-25-analysis-h1-7-deported-from-the-us?source=website" target="_blank">deported from the US</a> after criminal convictions and loss of judicial status. Instead of being welcomed home, Bhutan rejected them, and they ended up in the same refugee camps they once left under a <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-22-jul-25-analysis-h1-8-un-resettlement-program?source=website" target="_blank">UN resettlement program</a>.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
         <strong>On the ground:</strong> Upon arrival, Bhutanese authorities hand deportees a small amount of currency and send them to India, from where they often pay smugglers to enter Nepal. Nepal acknowledges the issue, but Bhutan is not ready to grant them citizenship. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
         Meanwhile, the refugees live in camps, surviving on family remittances, with no citizenship, documents, or liberty of movement. Analysts criticize the US deportation despite knowledge of minority persecution.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
        <strong>The background:</strong> Bhutan, a small Buddhist kingdom of roughly 800,000 people, has a history of crackdowns on ethnic minorities. In the late 1970s, Bhutan began its <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-22-jul-25-analysis-h1-9-crackdown-on-ethnic-nepalis?source=website" target="_blank">crackdown on ethnic Nepalis</a>, introducing policies designed to exclude Lhotshampa. From 1989, the government pushed the “Bhutanization” of the country by enforcing a dress code and banning the Nepali language. Faced with abuse, threats, and coercion, the Lhotshampa fled.
          </p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
