        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #a9a7af">
            <i>The Oslo District Court rules that holding Breivik in isolation does not violate his human rights. Credits: Atlantic</i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          <strong>The what:</strong> On July 22, 2011, Norway underwent <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-22-jul-25-foundations-h1-15-its-worst-attack?source=website" target="_blank">its worst attack</a> since World War II. A 32-year-old Norwegian, Anders Behring Breivik, detonated a fertilizer bomb outside the prime minister’s office in Oslo, which killed eight people. He then went to Utoya island, where a Labour Party youth camp was underway, killing 69 more people, mostly teenagers. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
      <strong>The motive:</strong> Breivik was a far-right extremist opposing multiculturalism, Islam, and liberal European values. He believed the Labour Party was facilitating the “Islamization” of Europe. He detailed his radical views and justified violence for political change in a manifesto, where he declared himself to be part of a broader anti-Muslim movement, but such a network didn't exist. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
       <Strong>The impact:</strong> Following the incident, more than 150,000 Norwegians gathered in Oslo carrying the red and white rose as a symbol of democracy and unity (<a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-22-jul-25-foundations-h1-16-rose-march?source=website" target="_blank">rose march</a>). The tragedy pushed Norway to focus more on domestic extremism and security. Breivik was eventually declared sane and sentenced to 21 years in prison, with the possibility of indefinite extension. 
          </p>
        </mj-text>
